'''Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun''' (山湾照神社古壇, ''Yamatsuteru-jinja Kofun'') is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古壇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kofun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (ancient Kofun) located in [[:en:Maibara, Shiga|Maibara City]], [[:en:Shiga Prefecture|Shiga Prefecture]]. It features a {{ill|zenpō-kōen-fun|ja|前方後土壇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōen-fun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (keyhole-shaped tumulus) design and is part of the Okina Kofun Cluster. Designated as a Shiga Prefectural Historic Site, the burial goods excavated from the site are also recognized as Shiga Prefectural Historic Site.

== Overview ==
[[File:Yamatsuteru-jinja Kofun, funkyu-2.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Kofun (north side)}}{{small|Front square on the right, back round on the left.}]]
The kofun is located at the southern edge of the Yokoyama Hills in the northeastern part of Shiga Prefecture (Hokubu Region). It is one of the representative late-period tumuli in the Hokubu Region{{Sfn|Investigation of Okina Town Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|1995}}. Together with other mounds such as Tsuka-no-Koshi Kofun, Gobettō Kofun, Hitotsukayama Kofun, and Kitsunezuka Kofun, it types the Okina Kofun Cluster{{Sfn|Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun (Heibonsha)|1991}}. Presently, it is situated within the precincts of the {{ill|Yamatsuteru Shrine|ja|山湾照神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatsuteru Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and was discovered during shrine construction work in 1882 (Meiji 15). At that time, a Sarcophagus and burial goods were unearthed<ref name="Additional designation1"/>. Parts of the mound have been leveled over time, and in 1994 (Heisei 6), an investigation by Kyoto University was conducted<ref name="Additional designation1"/>.

The mound has a developed keyhole-shaped design typical of the late tumulus period, with the front square facing west. It measures 46.2 meters in length. Although no terraced construction or stone covering has been identified, "Iwami-style" shield-shaped haniwa and cylindrical haniwa have been arranged. Ritual sites in the northern constricted area suggest the possible existence of a {{ill|Tsukuri-dashi|ja|造出|1=Platform-style projection|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukuri-dashi|13=User:Immanuelle/Platform-style projection|qq=}} structure{{Sfn|Investigation of Okina Town Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|1995}}. No surrounding moat has been found{{Sfn|Investigation of Okina Town Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|1995}}. The burial facility features a yokoana-style stone chamber containing an iegata-sekkan. Excavations in the Meiji period revealed numerous grave goods, including gilt-bronze crowns, swords, and crystal magatama beads<ref name="Additional designation1"/>.

The mound is estimated to have been constructed in the mid-6th century during the late Kofun period{{Sfn|Investigation of Okina Town Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|1995}}<ref name="Additional designation1"/>. It is considered the successor to the Tsuka-no-Koshi Kofun as the chieftain’s tomb within the Okina Kofun Cluster{{Sfn|Investigation of Okina Town Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|1995}} and the last keyhole-shaped tumulus in the [[:en:Sakata District, Shiga|Sakata District]] area{{Sfn|Chiaki Mizutani|2013|pp=76-97}}. The cluster is believed to be the burial site for chieftains of the Okina Clan, with this kofun being one of their key tombs{{Sfn|Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun (Heibonsha)|1991}}{{Sfn|Chiaki Mizutani|2013|pp=76-97}}. Historically, it was even speculated to be the tomb of {{ill|Prince Okina|ja|恩長宿禦王|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Okina|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, father of [[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]]{{Sfn|Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}.

== Archaeological Timeline ==
* [[:en:1882|1882]]: Discovered during shrine construction, uncovering Sarcophaguss and burial goods{{Sfn|Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun (Heibonsha)|1991}}<ref name="Additional designation1"/>.
* [[:en:1940|1940]]: Excavation of burial goods conducted by Kyoto University Archaeology Laboratory{{Sfn|Investigation of Okina Town Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|1995}}.
* [[:en:1957|1957]]: Majority of burial goods Historic Site1 as Shiga Prefectural Historic Site (August 26)<ref name="Disaster Plan"/>.
* [[:en:1969|1969]]: Designated as a Shiga Prefectural Historic Site (September 12)<ref name="Disaster Plan"/>.
* [[:en:1994|1994]]: Survey and excavation of the mound conducted by Kyoto University Archaeology Laboratory{{Sfn|Investigation of Okina Town Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|1995}}<ref name="Additional designation1"/>.
* [[:en:1996|1996]]: burial goods not previously Historic Site1 were recognized as cultural properties by Okina Town (later Maibara City)<ref name="Disaster Plan"/>.
* [[:en:2006|2006]]: Additional burial goods were included in the Shiga Prefectural Historic Site listing (March 17)<ref name="Disaster Plan"/>.

== Historic Site ==
=== Shiga Prefectural Historic Site ===
* Historic Site:
** burial goods excavated from Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun
*** Items include gilt-bronze crowns, iron swords, ceremonial pottery, and decorative fittings. Since 1961, most burial goods have been housed at the {{ill|Lake Biwa Museum|ja|湖濱博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lake Biwa Museum|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, with some later transferred to the {{ill|Azuchi Castle Archaeology Museum|ja|安園城考古博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Azuchi Castle Archaeology Museum|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.
*** First Historic Site: August 26, 1957; additional Historic Site: March 17, 2006.
* Historic Site:
** Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun - Designated September 12, 1969.

